## Set up next-safe-action v7 in Next.js App Router

### 1. Install packages
- Run: `npm install next-safe-action zod`
- `zod` is a peer dependency required for schema validation.
- next-safe-action v7 targets Next.js 14+ with App Router and React 18+.

### 2. Create the safe action client
- Create `src/lib/safe-action.ts`:
```ts
import { createSafeActionClient } from 'next-safe-action';

export const actionClient = createSafeActionClient();
```
- This is the base client. You will extend it with middleware in the next steps.

### 3. Add authentication middleware
- Extend the base client with auth middleware — create `src/lib/safe-action.ts` (or update it):
```ts
import { createSafeActionClient } from 'next-safe-action';
import { auth } from '@/lib/auth'; // your session function (Clerk, Auth.js, etc.)

export const actionClient = createSafeActionClient();

export const authActionClient = actionClient.use(async ({ next }) => {
  const session = await auth();

  if (!session?.user) {
    throw new Error('Unauthorized');
  }

  return next({ ctx: { user: session.user } });
});
```
- `authActionClient` injects `ctx.user` into every action that uses it — no per-action auth checks needed.
- Use `actionClient` for public actions, `authActionClient` for protected ones.

### 4. Define your first Server Action
- Create `src/actions/create-post.ts`:
```ts
'use server';

import { z } from 'zod';
import { authActionClient } from '@/lib/safe-action';
import { db } from '@/db';

const schema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1).max(100),
  body: z.string().min(1).max(5000),
});

export const createPost = authActionClient
  .schema(schema)
  .action(async ({ parsedInput, ctx }) => {
    const post = await db.post.create({
      data: {
        title: parsedInput.title,
        body: parsedInput.body,
        authorId: ctx.user.id,
      },
    });

    return { post };
  });
```
- `parsedInput` is fully typed from the Zod schema — no casting needed.
- `ctx` carries the user injected by middleware.
- The `'use server'` directive is required on the action file.

### 5. Call the action from a Server Component
- You can call actions directly in Server Components:
```tsx
// src/app/posts/page.tsx
import { createPost } from '@/actions/create-post';

export default async function PostsPage() {
  // Triggered by a form submit or button — shown here for illustration
  const result = await createPost({ title: 'Hello', body: 'World' });

  if (result?.serverError) {
    return <p>Error: {result.serverError}</p>;
  }

  return <p>Post created: {result?.data?.post.id}</p>;
}
```

### 6. Use the useAction hook in a Client Component
- `useAction` gives you loading state, optimistic updates, and typed callbacks:
```tsx
'use client';

import { useAction } from 'next-safe-action/hooks';
import { createPost } from '@/actions/create-post';

export function CreatePostForm() {
  const { execute, isPending, result } = useAction(createPost, {
    onSuccess: ({ data }) => {
      console.log('Created post:', data?.post.id);
    },
    onError: ({ error }) => {
      console.error('Validation or server error:', error);
    },
  });

  function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) {
    e.preventDefault();
    const formData = new FormData(e.currentTarget);
    execute({
      title: formData.get('title') as string,
      body: formData.get('body') as string,
    });
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input name="title" placeholder="Title" required />
      <textarea name="body" placeholder="Body" required />
      <button type="submit" disabled={isPending}>
        {isPending ? 'Creating...' : 'Create Post'}
      </button>
      {result.validationErrors && (
        <p>Validation error: {JSON.stringify(result.validationErrors)}</p>
      )}
    </form>
  );
}
```

### 7. Return typed errors from actions
- Use `returnValidationErrors` for field-level error feedback:
```ts
import { returnValidationErrors } from 'next-safe-action';

export const createPost = authActionClient
  .schema(schema)
  .action(async ({ parsedInput, ctx }) => {
    const existing = await db.post.findFirst({
      where: { title: parsedInput.title, authorId: ctx.user.id },
    });

    if (existing) {
      returnValidationErrors(schema, {
        title: { _errors: ['You already have a post with this title.'] },
      });
    }

    const post = await db.post.create({ data: { ...parsedInput, authorId: ctx.user.id } });
    return { post };
  });
```
- These errors appear in `result.validationErrors` in the `useAction` hook.

### 8. Add logging middleware (optional)
- Extend `actionClient` with a logging middleware:
```ts
export const actionClient = createSafeActionClient().use(async ({ next, metadata }) => {
  const startTime = performance.now();
  const result = await next();
  const durationMs = performance.now() - startTime;
  console.log(`[action] ${durationMs.toFixed(1)}ms`);
  return result;
});
```

### 9. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev` and submit the `CreatePostForm`.
- Submit empty fields — confirm `validationErrors` appears.
- Submit valid data — confirm `onSuccess` fires and the post is created.
- Submit as an unauthenticated user — confirm `serverError: 'Unauthorized'` is returned.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Action must be exported from a 'use server' file`** — Add `'use server'` at the top of your action file, not just at the top of the function.
- **`parsedInput` type is `unknown`** — You forgot to call `.schema(yourZodSchema)` before `.action(...)`. Always chain `.schema()` first.
- **Middleware `ctx` is not typed** — The middleware `use()` callback must return `next({ ctx: { ... } })` with the data typed inline. TypeScript infers `ctx` from the return type.
- **`useAction` import fails** — Import from `'next-safe-action/hooks'`, NOT from `'next-safe-action'`.
- **Auth middleware throws but client sees no error details** — `serverError` is set to a generic message by default for security. Customize the error message in `createSafeActionClient({ handleReturnedServerError })`.
- **`returnValidationErrors` not found** — You are on an older version. Update to next-safe-action v7: `npm install next-safe-action@latest`.
- **Action runs on client (no server execution)** — You forgot `'use server'` on the action file. Without it, the function runs in the browser and cannot access server-only resources.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT put `'use server'` only on the action function — it must be at the top of the file for Next.js to recognize all exports as server actions.
- Do NOT skip `.schema()` validation — raw `parsedInput` without a schema is typed as `undefined` and offers no protection against malformed input.
- Do NOT expose sensitive error details in `serverError` — customize `handleReturnedServerError` to return safe messages to clients while logging full errors on the server.
- Do NOT use `actionClient` (unauthenticated) for protected operations — always use `authActionClient` or equivalent for any action that modifies user-specific data.
- Do NOT define the Zod schema inline inside `.schema()` — extract it to a named variable so you can reuse it in `returnValidationErrors` and frontend form validation.
- Do NOT call `execute()` in a Server Component — `useAction` is a Client Component hook. Use direct `await action(input)` calls in Server Components instead.
